        "metadata": {
          "url": "https://www.cjr.org/business_of_news/for-journalists-ukraine-is-a-whatsapp-war.php",
          "title": "For journalists, Ukraine is a WhatsApp War",
          "description": "<p>Lindsey Hilsum, a correspondent for Britain’s Channel 4 News, is one the most experienced conflict reporters covering the Ukraine war. But she never heads out without an electronic tracking device that allows editors to monitor her every move. She is in constant and nearly instantaneous contact w…",
          "author": "Joel Simon",
          "publisher": "Columbia Journalism Review",
          "thumbnail": "https://www.cjr.org/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/AP_22060425612766-800x419.jpg?122376",
          "icon": "https://www.cjr.org/wp-content/themes/cjr2017/_resources2015/img/favicon-152.png"
        }
      }
    ],
    [
      "markdown",
      {
        "markdown": "> So how can we regain authenticity? What if you want to know what a genuine real life human being thinks about the latest Lenovo laptop?\n> You append “reddit\" to your query (or hacker news, or stack overflow, or some other community you trust).\n> Google is dead.\n> Long live Google + “site:reddit.com”."
      }
